  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates record-keeping and reporting of currency transactions\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Makes money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Prohibits conducting financial transactions with proceeds from illegal activities\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Enhanced money laundering prevention measures\n- Expanded reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Increased penalties for money laundering activities\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and strengthened existing anti-money laundering regulations\n- Increased transparency and reporting requirements\n- Expanded enforcement capabilities\n\nThese federal statutes provide comprehensive legal frameworks for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities. They establish reporting requirements, define criminal offenses, and set penalties for individuals and organizations involved in money laundering.\n\nAdditionally, individual states may have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\nFinancial institutions are required to comply with these laws by implementing robust compliance programs and reporting suspicious transactions to the relevant authorities.",
